# ============================================
# How to Find Your Camera's RTSP URL
# ============================================

# Method 1: Check camera/DVR manual
#   - Look for "RTSP URL" or "Streaming URL"
#   - Usually in network settings section

# Method 2: Use ONVIF Device Manager (Windows)
#   - Download from: https://sourceforge.net/projects/onvifdm/
#   - Scan your network
#   - Find camera, check "Live Video" section

# Method 3: Use ONVIF Device Tool (cross-platform)
#   - Similar to above but works on Linux/Mac

# Method 4: Check with VLC
#   - Open VLC → Media → Open Network Stream
#   - Try common formats: rtsp://IP:554/...
#   - If it works, you found it!

# Method 5: Test with ffprobe
#   ffprobe -rtsp_transport tcp "rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:554/stream1"
#   - Try different paths until you get video info

# ============================================
# Common RTSP Ports
# ============================================
# Default: 554
# Alternative: 555, 8554, 88
#
# If 554 doesn't work, try:
# rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:555/...
# rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:8554/...

# ============================================
# Testing Your URL
# ============================================
# Test with ffprobe to see codec info:
# ffprobe -rtsp_transport tcp "rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:554/your/path" 2>&1 | grep -i codec

# Test with ffplay to view the stream:
# ffplay -rtsp_transport tcp "rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:554/your/path"

# Test with VLC:
# vlc "rtsp://admin:password@192.168.1.100:554/your/path"

